    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.16.32"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                
                <note><hi rend="underline"><hi rend="caps">C O P Y</hi></hi></note>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">32</fw>
                  
                <fw type="imprint">
                    <hi rend="italics">The Limited Editions Club</hi> <hi rend="caps">INC.</hi> 551 <hi rend="italics">Fifth Avenue, New York</hi>
                        <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italics">Telephone</hi> <hi rend="caps">MURRAY HILL</hi> 2&#8212;1695-1696  <hi rend="italics">Cables</hi> <hi rend="caps">LIMITBOOKS</hi>
                
                    <figure>
                        <figDesc>Drawing, within a circle, representing three people reading books</figDesc>
                    </figure>
                </fw>
               
                <opener>
                    <dateline>September 23 1935</dateline>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>care of Mr. Charles <hi rend="caps">W.</hi> Kelly</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>473 First Avenue</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Salt Lake City, Utah</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>We are all pleased indeed, that you have agreed to represent your State in the committee of nominators for The Limited Editions Club's Gold Medal.</p>
                
                <p>We are anxious that the first award prove impressive; that the Gold Medal be awarded, on this first occasion, in such a manner that it will set the proper standard for future annual awards. For that reason, we have made a change in our plans. The first award is to cover a period of three years: it will be made to that book, published in 1932 or 1933 or 1934, which is considered to be most nearly a classic.</p>
                
                <p>Will you not make your nomination now on this basis?  Please nominate for us the book which you consider to be most nearly a classic, written by an American, and published in 1932 or 1933 or 1934.</p>
                
                <p>The selecting comittee will meet, to make the final selection from the nominations, on Monday October 7. I hope you can have your own nomination in our hands before that day.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Cordially yours</salute>
                    <signed>Carl Van Doren</signed>
                    <signed>Carl Van Doren
                    Chairman</signed>
                
                    <note>cvd.B</note>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
